args:
After defeating the white-wolf dragon, the party
is confronted by Harle. But when the injured
dragon rises to fight again—along with fiends
and a host of Church soldiers—he scurries
away. Notte then hears of a mysterious cave,
and the party decides to make a break for it.
Whatever could have caused a dragon\nto rage as this one did?
(It is not your fault the way did not open.)
(Someone—though I know not who—has\ncorrupted the lake's waters with miasma.)
Well, that's SUPER unhelpful.\nSo what do I do?
Oh, what a shame! I am undone.
Harle! What WAS that?\nAnd what are you even doing here?!
Well, well! If it isn't the traitor prince!\nOr I suppose I should just call you\nthe false prince now, hmm?
I will brook no insult to His Highness!
Ah, and the former Paladyn, as well.\nHow it warms the cockles of the heart\nto see you alive and kicking!

I entrusted you—and you alone—with the
truth, yet not only do you continue to
serve the prince, you actually RESIGNED
as Grand Paladyn! Ha ha! How delightful!
And Captain Gatov of the 12th Division\nWatch is with you as well! I've heard much\nand more about him from Cardinal Graht.
If you followed us all the way here,\nyou are a man of no mean skill.
It is beneath you to play the fool so.
On your guard against a nobody like me?\nOh, but you do not disappoint, Blazewolf.
Ain't ya got nothing better to do than waste\nour time, ya silver-tongued jerk?! I betcha\nsicced that dragon on us, too!
Why, I am positively WOUNDED that you\nwould suspect me—and without a shred\nof evidence, might I add. Tsk tsk tsk.
My, aren't we loquacious. Have you found\na new master from whose leash you can\nbark with borrowed authority, Harle?
I fear I never developed the taste for being\nfawned over as someone's family feline.

On the contrary, I seek only to flatter my
way into a master's good graces so I might
use them to my own ends—be that master
a royal family or even a church.
In any event, rather than slinging hurtful\naccusations at me, you might want to\nconsider dealing with that dragon.
We've more to worry about here\nthan a dragon!
Fiends! Wait, AND Church Templars?\nWhat is going on here?!
Take care, Brother—fiends and soldiers\nboth have taken leave of their senses.
Damn you, Harle! What have you done?!
Such harsh words for a man who merely\nwanted to liven up the party.
I pray from the bottom of my heart that you\nsurmount this hardship and arrive safe and\nsound in the Faerie Kingdom.
But I fear I must take my leave. Ta!
Thank you, Sheila!\n...It seems we're completely surrounded.
So many enemies...\nI cannot even take their measure.
Dealing with this many foes at once\nwill be no easy task.
Then perhaps we should skip the fight and\njust head straight for the Faerie Kingdom.
Hang on, guys! I'll get it open!
(I fear you will not be able to use the\nentrance there for some time, Notte.)
Wait, why are we going to a cave?
(Therein lies the remnants of a gate\nwhich once served as a way to the\nFaerie Kingdom.)
(It has not served such a purpose for ages\nupon ages, but it should yet work.)
Is someone speaking to you again, Notte?
Yeah, and they say there's a gate to the\nFaerie Kingdom in some nearby cave?
Think we oughta trust the magic voice\nin Notte's noggin, boss?
I'd rather trust that than stay here\nand be overwhelmed by enemies.
Can you get us to this cave, Notte?
Sure thing! I mean, um, I thiiink so?
Then everyone get ready—we'll hack our\nway through the enemy front and make\na break for the cave!
